{{italic title}} [[File:Clamdigger.JPG|thumb| ''Clamdigger'']] '''''Clamdigger''''' is a bronze sculpture by [[Willem de Kooning]].<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!373144~!0#focus "Clamdigger, (sculpture)"]. ''SIRIS''</ref> It may have been inspired by "the men who [[Clam digging|dug for clams]] along the beaches" near his home in [[East Hampton (town), New York|East Hampton, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Clamdigger, the Beloved | work = Art&Seek | accessdate = 2014-05-06 | date = 2008-09-22 | url = http://artandseek.net/2008/09/22/clamdigger-the-beloved/ }}</ref> It has been described as one of his "extraordinarily tactile figurative sculptures" that "seemed pulled from the primordial ooze,"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Stevens | first = Mark | title = Willem de Kooning Still Dazzles | work = Smithsonian Magazine, Arts & Culture | accessdate = 2014-05-06 | date = 2014-10-21 | url = http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/willem-de-kooning-still-dazzles-74063391/?page=3 }}</ref> and "as part man, part creature of the mud and the shallows."<ref>{{Cite news | last = Russell | first = John | title = Art: The Sculpture of Willem de Kooning | accessdate = 2014-05-06 | date = 1983-05-20 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/20/arts/art-the-sculpture-of-willem-de-kooning.html }}</ref>
The sculpture was modeled in clay in 1972, and cast in bronze in 1976. It was his "first large-scale bronze work."<ref>{{Cite web | title = Secondary Object | work = Museumland | accessdate = 2014-05-06 | date = 2014 | url = http://allisonmartindc.wordpress.com/secondary-object/ }}</ref>
As of 2014, ''Clamdigger'' is on display in the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hirshhorn.si.edu/visit/collection_object.asp?key=32&subkey=5909|title=Collection Search - Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden - Smithsonian|work=Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden - Smithsonian}}</ref>
De Kooning, known for his [[abstract expressionist]] paintings, took up sculpture later in his career, after a 1969 visit with a friend in [[Italy]] "who had a small [[foundry]]."<ref>{{Cite web | title = BAM/PFA - Art Exhibitions - Willem de Kooning | work = MATRIX 12 | accessdate = 2014-05-06 | url = http://www.bampfa.berkeley.edu/exhibition/12 }}</ref>
