{{italics title}}

'''''Gloucester County School Board v. G.G.''''' is a cancelled case<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/supreme-court-scraps-transgender-bathroom-rights-235712|title=High court sidesteps ruling on transgender rights|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref> that was supposed to be heard before the [[United States Supreme Court]].<ref name="wpost">{{cite web|last1=Barnes|first1=Robert|last2=Balingit|first2=Moriah|title=Supreme Court takes up school bathroom rules for transgender students|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/courts_law/supreme-court-takes-up-school-bathroom-rules-for-transgender-students/2016/10/28/0eece4ea-917f-11e6-a6a3-d50061aa9fae_story.html|website=Washington Post|accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> It would have been the Court's first case addressing [[transgender rights]]. It was filed by the ACLU.<ref name="aclu">{{cite web|title=G.G. v. Gloucester County School Board|url=https://www.aclu.org/cases/gg-v-gloucester-county-school-board|website=American Civil Liberties Union|accessdate=17 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> Oral argument was originally scheduled for March 28, 2017. The Supreme Court returned the case to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 4th Circuit after the Trump administration reversed the Executive Order which allowed G.G. to use the bathroom of his choice in the first place.

