{{distinguish|Pastoral epistles}}
A '''pastoral letter''', often called simply a '''pastoral''', is an [[open letter]] addressed by a [[bishop]] to the [[clergy]] or [[laity]] of a [[diocese]] or to both, containing general admonition, instruction or consolation, or directions for behaviour in particular circumstances. In the [[Catholic Church]], such letters are also sent out regularly at particular [[ecclesiastical]] seasons, particularly at the beginning of [[fasting|fasts]].<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Pastoral Letter |volume=20 |page=898 |inline=1}}</ref> In most episcopal church bodies, clerics are often required to read out pastoral letters of superior bishops to their congregations. 

In the non-[[episcopal polity|episcopal]] [[Protestant]] [[church body|churches]] a pastoral letter is any open letter addressed by a [[pastor]] to his congregation, more especially to one customarily issued at certain seasons, for example, by the moderator of a [[Presbyterian]] assembly or the chairman of a [[Congregational church|Congregational]] or [[Baptist]] union.<ref name=EB1911/>

